"""
mkt-context | 1 Samuel | chapters 1–3
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1samuel-1-3.py

Key themes: Shiloh as central sanctuary (late Judges period); Hannah/Peninnah
polygamy dynamics; barren-woman literary pattern (Sarah, Rachel, Manoah's wife,
Elizabeth); the Nazirite vow over Samuel; silent prayer as unusual (Eli's
misreading); Hannah's Song as reversal theology (Magnificat prototype);
Eli's corrupt sons and the fall of Shiloh priesthood; Samuel's prophetic call
as a type of the New Covenant word breaking silence; the "anointed one"
first mentioned at 2:10.

Verses already present in output: ch1 v1,3,9,20; ch2 v1,12,27,35; ch3 v1,3,19
merge_comm skips them.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent


def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / layer / f"{book}.json"
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}


def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / layer / f"{book}.json"
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f"  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}")


def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html
    return existing


SAMUEL1 = {
    "1": {
        "2": "<p>Elkanah had two wives &mdash; Hannah and Peninnah &mdash; a polygamous household legally permitted under Mosaic law but never idealized in the narrative. Peninnah had children; Hannah had none. The names are significant: Hannah (<em>channah</em>) = grace/favor; Peninnah = coral/pearl (a name associated with beauty and fecundity). The barren-plus-fertile co-wife pattern echoes Rachel and Leah (Gen 29-30), Sarah and Hagar (Gen 16), and anticipates Elizabeth and the societal pressure of her barrenness (Luke 1:25). In all these cases, the divinely significant birth comes through the woman marked by apparent disadvantage.</p>",
        "4": "<p>At the time of his annual sacrifice, Elkanah distributed portions (<em>manot</em>) to Peninnah and all her children. The distribution of sacrificial meat was the shared meal component of the <em>shelamim</em> (peace/fellowship offering), eaten by the worshiper and family rather than consumed on the altar. Deut 16:14 specifies that festival celebrations should include household members &mdash; but the unequal distribution here becomes the social fault line of the narrative. The sacrifice meant to foster family solidarity instead exposes its fracture.</p>",
        "5": "<p>Elkanah gave Hannah a special portion &ldquo;because he loved her, even though the LORD had closed her womb.&rdquo; The narrator attributes Hannah&rsquo;s barrenness to YHWH directly: <em>ki-et Hannah ahev vaYHWH sagar rachamah</em>. This is the specific narrative theology of the barren-woman pattern: YHWH closes the womb of the one through whom he will work, so that the birth is unambiguously an act of divine grace. The closed womb is the signature of a special divine design (cf. Gen 20:18; 25:21; 29:31; Judg 13:2-3).</p>",
        "6": "<p>Peninnah (<em>tzaratah</em>, her rival/adversary &mdash; the word also denotes a co-wife, related to <em>tzarah</em>, trouble/distress) provoked Hannah bitterly to irritate her &ldquo;because the LORD had closed her womb.&rdquo; The social pressure of barrenness in the ancient Near East was crushing: childlessness implied divine disfavor and meant no heir. Peninnah weaponizes this cultural shame. The Hebrew <em>ka&rsquo;as</em> (provoke, vex) denotes deep emotional pain rather than surface annoyance.</p>",
        "7": "<p>&ldquo;This went on year after year&rdquo; &mdash; the annual pilgrimage to Shiloh (the central sanctuary during the judges period, located in Ephraim approximately 30 km north of Jerusalem) becomes the occasion for repeated torment. Shiloh housed the tabernacle ark after the conquest (Josh 18:1) and functioned as the primary sacrificial center for roughly 300 years until its destruction, likely by the Philistines after the battle of Aphek (1 Sam 4), as confirmed by Jer 7:12: &ldquo;Go now to my place that was in Shiloh, where I made my name dwell at first, and see what I did to it.&rdquo; Hannah&rsquo;s grief interrupts the festival meal: she weeps and cannot eat.</p>",
        "8": "<p>Elkanah&rsquo;s question &mdash; &ldquo;Am I not more to you than ten sons?&rdquo; &mdash; is well-intentioned but tone-deaf. He interprets Hannah&rsquo;s grief as inadequate appreciation for his love, missing that her sorrow is about her standing before God and society. Ten (<em>asarah</em>) is a symbolic number of completeness. Elkanah&rsquo;s consolation echoes the human attempts to compensate for what only God can give &mdash; paralleled when the disciples try to redirect the blind man&rsquo;s cry to Jesus (Mark 10:48). Human provision cannot substitute for divine fulfillment.</p>",
        "10": "<p>Hannah was &ldquo;deeply distressed (<em>marat nefesh</em>, bitter of soul)&rdquo; and prayed to YHWH weeping bitterly (<em>bakoh tivkeh</em>, the infinitive absolute intensifying the main verb). Her approach to YHWH is unmediated, bypassing the priestly intermediary. The juxtaposition with Eli sitting by the doorpost emphasizes that Hannah goes directly to God. This directness &mdash; the bitterly distressed woman approaching YHWH herself &mdash; is a prototype of the access to God Jesus teaches in Luke 18:1-8 (the persistent widow) and embodies in his own intercessory approach.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Hannah&rsquo;s vow is conditional (<em>neder</em>): if YHWH gives her a son, she will give him back to YHWH all his days, and &ldquo;no razor shall touch his head (<em>mora lo ya&rsquo;aleh al rosho</em>).&rdquo; This is the Nazirite dedication formula from Num 6:5. Hannah consecrates her unborn son to a lifetime Nazirite vow &mdash; a state of special holiness. The only lifetime Nazirites in the OT are Samson (Judg 13:5) and Samuel himself; John the Baptist shares the pattern (Luke 1:15: &ldquo;he must never drink wine or other fermented drink&rdquo;). Hannah&rsquo;s radical act: she asks for a son in order to give him away permanently. The gift returned to the giver is the defining logic of consecration.</p>",
        "12": "<p>Eli, positioned as the professional guardian of sacred space, watches Hannah&rsquo;s mouth while she prays. His surveillance is that of a professional arbiter of propriety rather than a spiritual companion. Ancient Near Eastern prayer was normally audible &mdash; Mesopotamian and Egyptian prayer literature describes spoken petitions, and the temple liturgy assumed vocal confession and petition. Silent interior prayer was rare enough that Eli&rsquo;s misinterpretation is historically plausible, not merely character deficiency. He sees lip movement without sound and concludes intoxication.</p>",
        "13": "<p>Hannah speaks in her heart (<em>medabberet al libbah</em>); only her lips move. This is the first description of purely interior prayer in the Hebrew Bible &mdash; prayer as direct address to God from the inner person without performance or audibility. Ps 19:14 (&ldquo;may the meditation of my heart be pleasing to you&rdquo;) and later inward-prayer spirituality builds on this. The contrast between Hannah&rsquo;s interior intensity and the formal temple setting makes her an emblem of authentic spiritual communication. Jesus&rsquo; teaching in Matt 6:6 &mdash; &ldquo;pray to your Father who is in secret&rdquo; &mdash; elevates the principle of private, non-performative prayer that Hannah models here.</p>",
        "14": "<p>Eli&rsquo;s rebuke reveals the failure of discernment: he mistakes genuine spiritual distress for its social opposite (intoxication). Festivals did involve feasting (Amos 2:8 condemns those who drink wine beside altars), so drunkenness at the sanctuary was not unknown. The misreading of genuine spiritual experience as disorder is a recurrent pattern: the Pentecost outpouring is similarly misread (Acts 2:13: &ldquo;They are full of new wine&rdquo;). Eli&rsquo;s accusation is contextually plausible but spiritually wrong.</p>",
        "15": "<p>Hannah&rsquo;s self-defense: &ldquo;I have been pouring out my soul (<em>eshtopek et napshi</em>) before the LORD.&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;pouring out my soul&rdquo; (<em>shaphak nefesh</em>) is a striking image of total self-disclosure to God. Ps 62:8 uses the same idiom: &ldquo;Pour out your heart before him.&rdquo; Lam 2:19: &ldquo;Pour out your heart like water before the face of the Lord.&rdquo; The distinction between <em>yayin</em> (wine) and <em>shekar</em> (strong drink) encompasses the full range of fermented beverages &mdash; Hannah&rsquo;s denial is total.</p>",
        "16": "<p>&ldquo;Do not take your servant for a worthless woman (<em>bat beliyya&rsquo;al</em>).&rdquo; The term <em>beliyya&rsquo;al</em> (literally &ldquo;without profit/worth&rdquo;) is used elsewhere in 1 Samuel for Eli&rsquo;s own sons (2:12: <em>benei beliyya&rsquo;al</em>). Hannah protests that she is not what Eli&rsquo;s corrupt sons represent. The irony that the priest who cannot identify genuine piety is the father of the most glaring examples of impiety deepens throughout the narrative.</p>",
        "17": "<p>Eli&rsquo;s priestly benediction shifts the encounter from accusation to blessing: &ldquo;Go in peace (<em>lekhi le-shalom</em>), and may the God of Israel grant your petition (<em>she&rsquo;elah</em>) that you have asked of him.&rdquo; The word <em>she&rsquo;elah</em> (petition) connects to the child&rsquo;s name: Samuel (<em>Shemu&rsquo;el</em>), explained etymologically as &ldquo;asked of God&rdquo; in v. 20 &mdash; though the etymology may also play on <em>shema&rsquo; + el</em> (God has heard). The name Saul (<em>sha&rsquo;ul</em>) will later haunt this etymology: the king the people &ldquo;asked for&rdquo; versus the servant of God who was &ldquo;asked from&rdquo; YHWH.</p>",
        "18": "<p>After Eli&rsquo;s blessing, Hannah returned and ate, and &ldquo;her face was no longer downcast.&rdquo; The transformation precedes the actual granting of the request &mdash; she departs in trust before the pregnancy. This faith-before-fulfillment pattern is characteristic of the prayer-of-faith model: the answer to prayer is received in trust before it is received in fact. Heb 11:1 defines faith as &ldquo;the assurance of things hoped for, the conviction of things not seen.&rdquo; Hannah demonstrates this: the petition lodged with God has the quality of completed action in the heart before it materializes in history.</p>",
        "19": "<p>The next morning they worshiped and returned to Ramah. &ldquo;The LORD remembered her (<em>vayizkerah YHWH</em>).&rdquo; Divine remembrance (<em>zakar</em>) is a covenant term throughout the OT: YHWH remembered Noah (Gen 8:1), remembered Abraham (Gen 19:29), remembered Rachel (Gen 30:22). The remembrance is not mere mental recall but active attention that issues in transformative action. The same verb is used for YHWH&rsquo;s covenant faithfulness in Exod 2:24 (&ldquo;God remembered his covenant with Abraham&rdquo;). God&rsquo;s memory creates history.</p>",
        "21": "<p>Elkanah went up to offer the yearly sacrifice and fulfill his vow. Hannah did not accompany him, explaining she would wait until the child is weaned. Ancient Near Eastern weaning occurred at approximately two to three years of age. Num 6:13-21 specifies that the completion of a Nazirite vow required a presentation at the sanctuary with specified offerings; Hannah&rsquo;s delay until weaning ensures Samuel is old enough to remain at the sanctuary independently.</p>",
        "22": "<p>Hannah&rsquo;s plan: &ldquo;As soon as the child is weaned, I will bring him, that he may appear before the LORD and remain there permanently (<em>ve-yashav sham &rsquo;ad-&rsquo;olam</em>).&rdquo; The word <em>&rsquo;olam</em> (forever, perpetually) signals the irreversibility of the vow. The child-given-back-permanently prefigures the gift of the Son: &ldquo;God so loved the world that he gave his only Son&rdquo; (John 3:16) &mdash; the supreme gift that does not return. Hannah&rsquo;s sacrifice of her son is a type of the Father&rsquo;s gift of his Son.</p>",
        "23": "<p>Elkanah defers to Hannah: &ldquo;Only, may the LORD establish his word (<em>yaqem YHWH et devaro</em>).&rdquo; This prayer for the establishment of the divine word anticipates a theological principle central to all prophetic texts: divine words are not mere statements but self-realizing acts that YHWH &ldquo;establishes&rdquo; in history. Isa 55:11: &ldquo;so shall my word be that goes out from my mouth; it shall not return to me empty, but it shall accomplish that which I purpose.&rdquo;</p>",
        "24": "<p>At weaning, Hannah brought Samuel to Shiloh with a substantial offering: a three-year-old bull, an ephah of flour (approximately 22 liters), and a skin of wine. The offering exceeds the normal Nazirite completion offering of Num 6:14, suggesting a celebratory freewill offering beyond the vow requirements. The note &ldquo;the child was still young (<em>veha-na&rsquo;ar na&rsquo;ar</em>)&rdquo; uses the term <em>na&rsquo;ar</em> twice in the same sentence &mdash; a rare reduplication that emphasizes the poignancy of bringing such a small child for permanent dedication.</p>",
        "25": "<p>They slaughtered the bull and brought the child to Eli. The slaughter precedes the presentation; the offering and the dedicant are brought together in the same gesture. The imagery of sacrifice accompanying the presentation of a consecrated son surfaces again in Luke 2:22-24, when Mary and Joseph bring Jesus to the temple with the required offering (two turtledoves). Luke&rsquo;s nativity account is constructed with the Samuel narrative as a template: barren mothers, priestly figures, hymns of reversal (Hannah&rsquo;s Song / Magnificat), and the child dedicated at the sanctuary.</p>",
        "26": "<p>Hannah presents herself to Eli with the idiomatic oath formula: &ldquo;As you live, my lord.&rdquo; She identifies herself as the woman who prayed at this very spot. The emphasis on location &mdash; <em>nitzavti immekha bazeh</em> (standing with you here) &mdash; marks the exact site of her prayer as sacred. Hannah returns to the point of her deepest distress to complete the covenant transaction. The same spot where Eli misread her as drunk is where she fulfills her vow. Sacred geography often works this way: the place of encounter becomes the place of fulfillment (Gen 28:16-22: Jacob&rsquo;s vow at Bethel completed at Bethel).</p>",
        "27": "<p>&ldquo;For this child I prayed (<em>el-ha-na&rsquo;ar hazeh hitpallalti</em>), and the LORD has granted me my petition (<em>sha&rsquo;elati</em>) that I asked of him.&rdquo; The connection between petition and answer is explicit and personal: this specific child is the answer to this specific prayer. The word <em>sha&rsquo;elati</em> (my petition) will be embedded in the child&rsquo;s name. The pattern of prayer-answered-in-a-person is structurally significant: Isaac (Abraham&rsquo;s intercession, Gen 20:17), Samson (his mother&rsquo;s vow, Judg 13), John the Baptist (Elizabeth&rsquo;s answered prayer, Luke 1:13), and ultimately Jesus as the deepest answer to all Israel&rsquo;s petitions.</p>",
        "28": "<p>&ldquo;Therefore I have given him back (<em>ve-gam anokhi hish&rsquo;iltîhu</em>) to the LORD. As long as he lives, he belongs to the LORD.&rdquo; The verb <em>sha&rsquo;al</em> (to ask/lend) takes on a technical sense: Hannah &ldquo;lends&rdquo; Samuel back to YHWH &mdash; another reading of the name: &ldquo;the one lent to God.&rdquo; The act of giving back what was asked for is the culmination of the logic of grace: Hannah receives the gift in order to return it. Deut 26:1-11 ritualizes first fruits on this same logic: you receive the land&rsquo;s produce as YHWH&rsquo;s gift, then offer it back in acknowledgment of the source.</p>",
    },
    "2": {
        "2": "<p>&ldquo;There is no one holy like the LORD (<em>ein qadosh kaYHWH</em>); there is no one besides you (<em>ki ein biltekha</em>); there is no rock (<em>tzur</em>) like our God.&rdquo; The rock imagery is the divine-warrior epithet of the Song of Moses (Deut 32:4, 15, 18, 30-31). Hannah&rsquo;s song echoes Mosaic theology deliberately. The incomparability formula (<em>ein...ki...ein</em>) became the structural backbone of Deutero-Isaiah&rsquo;s monotheistic polemic: &ldquo;Is there a God besides me? There is no Rock; I know not any&rdquo; (Isa 44:8). Both YHWH&rsquo;s uniqueness and his rock-character point to absolute reliability &mdash; the ground of Hannah&rsquo;s confidence in a world that seemed to offer her nothing.</p>",
        "3": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD is a God of knowledge (<em>el de&rsquo;ot</em>), and by him deeds are weighed (<em>ve-lo nitkenû &rsquo;alilot</em>).&rdquo; The plural <em>de&rsquo;ot</em> (knowledges) is unique to this text &mdash; it implies comprehensive omniscience from all angles simultaneously. The weighing of deeds recalls the Egyptian <em>maat</em> (truth-balance) concept but roots it in YHWH&rsquo;s personal assessment. The verse is a theological counter to Peninnah&rsquo;s boasting: pride in fertility will be exposed when YHWH&rsquo;s comprehensive assessment is applied.</p>",
        "4": "<p>&ldquo;The bows of the mighty (<em>gibborim</em>) are shattered (<em>chatim</em>), but those who stumbled (<em>nikhshalim</em>) are girded with strength.&rdquo; The first of the song&rsquo;s reversal pairs. Military might is broken while the weak are empowered. Ps 46:9 (&ldquo;he breaks the bow and shatters the spear&rdquo;) participates in the same divine-warrior-reversal theology. Luke 1:51-52 (Magnificat) quotes this logic directly: &ldquo;He has scattered the proud... he has brought down the mighty from their thrones.&rdquo;</p>",
        "5": "<p>&ldquo;The barren woman has borne seven (<em>aqarah yaldah shivah</em>), but she who has many children languishes (<em>ummelet</em>).&rdquo; The seven-children image is the fullness of the reversal: the most barren woman now has the most fertile outcome. The number seven signals completeness. Hannah herself will bear five more children after Samuel (v. 21), totaling six &mdash; the &ldquo;seven&rdquo; may be hyperbolic or symbolic. Mary&rsquo;s Magnificat (Luke 1:53: &ldquo;he has filled the hungry with good things, and the rich he has sent away empty&rdquo;) translates Hannah&rsquo;s reversal-logic into the vocabulary of the new creation.</p>",
        "6": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD brings death and gives life (<em>YHWH memit umechayyeh</em>); he brings down to Sheol and raises up.&rdquo; YHWH&rsquo;s sovereign authority extends over the boundary between life and death. Deut 32:39 uses almost identical language: &ldquo;I put to death and I bring to life.&rdquo; This is the theological foundation for later resurrection hope: if YHWH commands both death and life, neither is a permanent condition beyond his reach. 1 Sam 2:6 is the OT root of what Paul develops in 1 Cor 15:26 (&ldquo;the last enemy to be destroyed is death&rdquo;) and what Jesus claims in John 11:25 (&ldquo;I am the resurrection and the life&rdquo;). Hannah sings resurrection theology before Israel has a vocabulary for it.</p>",
        "7": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD makes poor and makes rich (<em>YHWH morish uma&rsquo;ashir</em>); he brings low, and he also lifts up.&rdquo; Economic and social status are within YHWH&rsquo;s sovereign disposition. James 4:10 (&ldquo;humble yourselves before the Lord, and he will lift you up&rdquo;) and 1 Pet 5:6 echo this logic. The Beatitudes (Matt 5:3-10) are structured on this same schema: blessed are the poor, the mourners, the meek &mdash; those at the bottom of each social axis.</p>",
        "8": "<p>&ldquo;He raises the poor from the dust (<em>meqim me&rsquo;afar dal</em>) and lifts the needy from the ash heap, to seat them with princes and give them a throne of honor.&rdquo; The dust-to-throne reversal is the paradigmatic elevation narrative: Joseph from prison to Pharaoh&rsquo;s right hand, David from pasture to palace. The <em>ashpot</em> (dunghill) imagery denotes the most abject poverty (cf. Ps 113:7, which quotes this verse nearly verbatim). The verse concludes with cosmic grounding: &ldquo;for the pillars of the earth are YHWH&rsquo;s, and on them he has set the world.&rdquo; Social reversals are possible because YHWH is the cosmic architect whose jurisdiction is total.</p>",
        "9": "<p>&ldquo;He will guard the feet of his faithful ones (<em>chasidim</em>), but the wicked will be silenced in darkness, for not by strength does a man prevail (<em>ki-lo vechoach yigbar ish</em>).&rdquo; The <em>chasidim</em> (faithful ones, covenant loyal) are YHWH&rsquo;s protected community. The climactic claim &mdash; &ldquo;not by strength does a man prevail&rdquo; &mdash; is the theological summary of the entire reversal poem: human power is not the decisive variable in history. YHWH&rsquo;s sovereign ordering determines outcomes.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The song&rsquo;s climax: &ldquo;The LORD will judge the ends of the earth; he will give strength to his king (<em>melekho</em>) and lift high the horn of his anointed (<em>meshicho</em>).&rdquo; Remarkable: there was no king in Israel when Hannah sang this. The monarchy has not yet been established. Hannah speaks of a coming anointed king as part of YHWH&rsquo;s eschatological action. This is the first occurrence of <em>mashiach</em> (anointed one) in the narrative books, entirely prospective. The song anticipates the Davidic covenant (2 Sam 7), the Messianic psalms (Ps 2:2; 18:50; 89:51), and ultimately the identity of Jesus as <em>Christos</em> (the Greek translation of <em>mashiach</em>).</p>",
        "11": "<p>Elkanah returned to Ramah while Samuel remained at Shiloh to minister to YHWH (<em>meshareth et-YHWH</em>) in the presence of Eli. The term <em>shereth</em> (minister) is the standard term for Levitical and priestly service at the sanctuary (Num 18:2; Deut 10:8). The scene&rsquo;s pathos is understated: the family is permanently divided by the child&rsquo;s consecration. Samuel&rsquo;s service begins immediately upon his dedication.</p>",
        "13": "<p>The priests&rsquo; corrupt practice is detailed: when someone offered a sacrifice, the priest&rsquo;s servant would come with a three-pronged fork (<em>mazleg shelosh hashinnayim</em>) while the meat was boiling and take whatever the fork brought up. The <em>shelamim</em> (peace offering) procedure in Lev 7:28-36 specified that the breast and right thigh went to the priest &mdash; a specific, limited portion. Eli&rsquo;s sons circumvent this by taking from the communal pot before the worshiper&rsquo;s portion was served, an unspecified random amount. This is theft from the sacred meal that was intended to foster communion between YHWH, the priest, and the worshiper.</p>",
        "14": "<p>The fork was thrust indiscriminately into whatever vessel &mdash; pan, kettle, cauldron, or pot &mdash; and whatever came up was taken. The variety of cooking vessels mentioned suggests different parts of the sanctuary kitchen were affected. The practice was applied to &ldquo;all the Israelites who came to Shiloh&rdquo; &mdash; systemic, not occasional. The systemic exploitation of the sanctuary economy parallels the temple money-changers Jesus encounters in John 2:14-16: what should facilitate encounter with God has been turned into a mechanism for priestly enrichment.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The sons&rsquo; behavior escalates: they demanded raw meat even before the fat (<em>chelev</em>) was burned. The fat was YHWH&rsquo;s portion &mdash; Lev 3:16 mandates &ldquo;all the fat belongs to the LORD&rdquo; as &ldquo;an everlasting statute.&rdquo; Demanding raw meat before the divine portion inverts the entire sacrificial order: the worshiper&rsquo;s appetites precede YHWH&rsquo;s honor. This is not merely liturgical carelessness but theological inversion &mdash; prioritizing human appetites over divine honor in the very act designed to express the reverse.</p>",
        "16": "<p>When a worshiper tried to protest, the response was coercive: &ldquo;No, hand it over now; if not, I will take it by force (<em>velaqachti bekozek</em>).&rdquo; The use of force (<em>kozek</em>, power/violence) transforms a religious dispute into social coercion. This is the abusive-authority pattern condemned throughout the prophets: Amos 5:12 (those who take bribes and push the needy aside), Jer 7:11 (the temple as a den of robbers). The Shiloh sanctuary becomes the prototype against which all subsequent temple corruption is measured.</p>",
        "17": "<p>&ldquo;The sin of these young men was very great in the sight of the LORD, for they treated the LORD&rsquo;s offering (<em>minchat YHWH</em>) with contempt (<em>nave&rsquo;atztu</em>).&rdquo; The verb <em>nav&rsquo;atztu</em> (despised) is used in 2:30 for those who despise YHWH himself &mdash; the narrator equates contempt for YHWH&rsquo;s offering with contempt for YHWH. This anticipates the NT principle that abuse of the Lord&rsquo;s Supper constitutes sin &ldquo;against the body and blood of the Lord&rdquo; (1 Cor 11:27).</p>",
        "18": "<p>Samuel ministering before YHWH as a boy, clothed in a linen ephod (<em>ephod bad</em>) &mdash; the standard priestly vestment (2 Sam 6:14: David wears one while dancing before the ark). The contrast with Eli&rsquo;s sons is pointed: while they exploit the sanctuary, Samuel wears the garment of genuine service. The child dressed in priestly linen, devoted to YHWH before he can understand what that means, is a striking image of vocation preceding comprehension &mdash; as with John the Baptist leaping in the womb before cognitive awareness (Luke 1:44).</p>",
        "19": "<p>Hannah&rsquo;s annual visit with a new little robe (<em>me&rsquo;il qatan</em>) for Samuel. The <em>me&rsquo;il</em> was a standard outer garment; its small size marks the child&rsquo;s age and growth. The annual visit becomes a recurring liturgical act of reconnection: each year Hannah brings the robe as a token of her ongoing commitment to the vow. The garment grows larger each year as Samuel grows. The mother who gave her son away to God continues to clothe him &mdash; a beautiful image of ongoing maternal love within the structure of dedication.</p>",
        "20": "<p>Eli&rsquo;s annual blessing: &ldquo;May the LORD give you children by this woman in return for the gift (<em>ha-she&rsquo;ilah</em>) she has given to the LORD.&rdquo; The blessing reverses the expected economics of vows: normally you give something to get something. Here, the gift-given leads to more gifts received. Consecration is not a zero-sum transaction but an economics of abundance &mdash; giving to God generates more giving. Abraham&rsquo;s willingness to give Isaac leads to the oath of blessing (Gen 22:16-18).</p>",
        "21": "<p>The LORD visited (<em>paqad</em>) Hannah &mdash; the same verb used for YHWH&rsquo;s redemptive action with Sarah (Gen 21:1) and for the Exodus promise (Exod 3:16: &ldquo;I have surely visited you&rdquo;). Hannah bore three more sons and two daughters &mdash; six children in all. Samuel, meanwhile, &ldquo;grew up in the presence of the LORD (<em>im YHWH</em>).&rdquo; The phrase <em>im YHWH</em> signals intimate divine presence. Luke 2:52 uses similar language of Jesus: &ldquo;And Jesus increased in wisdom and in stature and in favor with God and man.&rdquo;</p>",
        "22": "<p>Eli was very old and heard about everything his sons did &mdash; including that they were &ldquo;sleeping with the women who served at the entrance to the tent of meeting (<em>ohel mo&rsquo;ed</em>).&rdquo; The tent of meeting reference uses the tabernacle terminology for the Shiloh sanctuary, connecting it to the Mosaic institution. The sexual misconduct of priests at the sanctuary recalls the Canaanite fertility cult practices explicitly condemned throughout Deuteronomy. Eli&rsquo;s sons have assimilated the worst of surrounding religious practice into YHWH&rsquo;s sanctuary.</p>",
        "23": "<p>Eli&rsquo;s rebuke is gentle: &ldquo;Why do you do such things? For I hear of your evil deeds from all these people.&rdquo; But the rebuke&rsquo;s gentleness is itself condemned by the divine perspective: Eli says &ldquo;I hear&rdquo; but does nothing more than speak. The passivity of effective tolerance is judged as severely as the sons&rsquo; active sin. 1 Sam 3:13 will specify YHWH&rsquo;s indictment: &ldquo;because his sons were blaspheming God and he did not rebuke them.&rdquo; Parental/leadership passivity in the face of flagrant sin is not neutrality but complicity.</p>",
        "24": "<p>&ldquo;It is not a good report (<em>lo-tovah hashemuah</em>) that I hear the LORD&rsquo;s people spreading.&rdquo; The concern is reputational: what people are saying. Eli&rsquo;s rebuke prioritizes the public report over the moral reality. The same failure appears in John 12:42-43 where leaders who believed in Jesus would not confess him &ldquo;for they loved human praise more than the praise of God.&rdquo; Eli&rsquo;s sons are not restrained because the rebuke is motivated by image-management rather than fidelity to YHWH.</p>",
        "25": "<p>&ldquo;But they would not listen to the voice of their father, for it was the will of the LORD to put them to death (<em>ki chaphetz YHWH lehavitam</em>).&rdquo; This is the hardening pattern of Pharaoh applied to Eli&rsquo;s sons: their refusal to repent and the divine determination to judge them are intertwined. The question Eli poses &mdash; &ldquo;if someone sins against the LORD, who will intercede for him (<em>mi yitpallel-bo</em>)?&rdquo; &mdash; is answered implicitly: no one can. This raises the deepest theological question that the NT answers: who can intercede for those whose sin is against YHWH? The one unique intercessor, Jesus Christ (1 Tim 2:5; Heb 7:25).</p>",
        "26": "<p>&ldquo;The young man Samuel continued to grow and to be in favor (<em>tov</em>) with the LORD and with men.&rdquo; This developmental summary deliberately contrasts Samuel&rsquo;s flourishing with the degeneration of Eli&rsquo;s house. The phrase <em>gam im YHWH vegam im anashim</em> (with YHWH and with men) is precisely echoed in Luke 2:52 about Jesus: &ldquo;Jesus increased in wisdom and in stature and in favor with God and man.&rdquo; Luke&rsquo;s language is not coincidental &mdash; the Samuel narrative is the template for the Lukan presentation of Jesus&rsquo; childhood.</p>",
        "28": "<p>The man of God reviews the Aaronic priestly election: &ldquo;I chose your ancestor from all the tribes of Israel to be my priest &mdash; to go up to my altar, to burn incense, and to wear the ephod before me.&rdquo; The three priestly functions &mdash; altar service, incense, ephod (oracular consultation) &mdash; represent the full range of sanctuary ministry. The historical election of the Aaronide line (Exod 28:1; Num 3:10) is rehearsed to establish the weight of the covenant being broken.</p>",
        "29": "<p>&ldquo;Why then do you despise my sacrifices and my offerings... and honor your sons more than me by fattening yourselves on the best parts?&rdquo; The accusation identifies the root sin: honoring sons above YHWH. Eli&rsquo;s failure is not ignorance but misplaced honor. This is the corruption of nepotism in religious clothing &mdash; the very thing Jesus condemns in Matt 15:4-6 when the Pharisees use &ldquo;Corban&rdquo; declarations to evade the commandment to honor parents: human religious arrangements used to circumvent divine commandments.</p>",
        "30": "<p>&ldquo;Those who honor me I will honor, and those who despise me will be treated with contempt (<em>yeqallu</em>).&rdquo; One of the clearest statements of divine reciprocity in the OT: the relationship between YHWH and his servants mirrors the relationship the servants maintain toward him. The revocability of dynastic promises based on covenant faithfulness applies to the Davidic dynasty (Ps 89:30-32; 1 Kgs 9:6-7) and is fulfilled when the entire priestly and royal system is replaced in Christ (Heb 7:11-12).</p>",
        "31": "<p>&ldquo;The days are coming when I will cut off your strength and the strength of your father&rsquo;s house, so that no man in your house will reach old age.&rdquo; The cutting off of the arm (<em>zerao&rsquo;</em>, arm = power/lineage) is a covenantal curse. Fulfilled when Doeg kills the priests of Nob (1 Sam 22:18-19) and when Solomon removes Abiathar (1 Kgs 2:26-27) &mdash; a fulfillment 1 Kgs 2:27 explicitly notes: &ldquo;to fulfill what the LORD had spoken concerning the house of Eli.&rdquo;</p>",
        "32": "<p>&ldquo;You will look with envy at all the good that will be done for Israel, but there will never be an old man in your house.&rdquo; The house of Eli will witness Israel&rsquo;s blessing from a position of irreversible exclusion. The pathos of covenant forfeiture: you see the abundance of what was available and know it has been squandered. The same structure appears when Israel watches Gentiles receive covenant status (Rom 11:11: &ldquo;through their trespass salvation has come to the Gentiles, so as to make Israel jealous&rdquo;).</p>",
        "33": "<p>One surviving member of Eli&rsquo;s house will be left at YHWH&rsquo;s altar, but only to &ldquo;consume your eyes with grief and break your heart (<em>le-dakke&rsquo;ot et-einekha uleda&rsquo;avon et-napshekha</em>).&rdquo; The Hebrew <em>dakke&rsquo;ot einekha</em> is an intense expression &mdash; literally &ldquo;to cause your eyes to languish/waste away.&rdquo; The sight of what could have been is more painful than ignorance of it.</p>",
        "34": "<p>&ldquo;This will be the sign (<em>ha-ot</em>) for you: both your sons, Hophni and Phinehas, shall die on the same day.&rdquo; A sign-in-advance that the oracle is reliable. Fulfilled in 1 Sam 4:11 when both sons die during the battle of Aphek and the Philistines capture the ark. The precision of the sign underlines YHWH&rsquo;s foreknowledge and control of events (cf. Deut 18:21-22: fulfilled prophecy as the criterion of true prophethood).</p>",
        "36": "<p>The prophecy ends with the humiliation of Eli&rsquo;s surviving descendants: they will beg the new faithful priest for &ldquo;a piece of silver or a loaf of bread&rdquo; just to serve in a minor priestly function. The reversal of their earlier wealth (fattening on the best portions, v. 29) into begging for bread is the perfect structural inversion. The oracle thus ends where Hannah&rsquo;s song began: with reversal. The faithful priest who will replace Eli&rsquo;s house is initially fulfilled in Zadok (replacing Abiathar under Solomon) and ultimately in Christ, the eternal high priest (Heb 5:5-6; 7:11-17).</p>",
    },
    "3": {
        "2": "<p>Eli, whose eyesight had grown so dim that he could no longer see, was lying down in his room. The detail of Eli&rsquo;s failing eyesight is both physically accurate for advanced age and symbolically loaded: the priest responsible for spiritual discernment cannot see clearly. The narrative has already shown his failure to discern Hannah&rsquo;s prayer and his failure to discipline his sons; now his physical blindness externalizes his spiritual state. Vision failures accompanying moral/discernment failures appear with Isaac (Gen 27:1) and form a recurring prophetic metaphor (Isa 6:9-10; John 9:39).</p>",
        "4": "<p>YHWH called, &ldquo;Samuel!&rdquo; and the boy answered, &ldquo;Here I am (<em>hinneni</em>).&rdquo; The response <em>hinneni</em> is the classic answer of readiness to divine call: Abraham at the Aqedah (Gen 22:1, 7, 11), Jacob at Bethel (Gen 46:2), Moses at the burning bush (Exod 3:4), Isaiah at the throne vision (Isa 6:8). It is the readiness-response of the servant before the sovereign. Samuel&rsquo;s immediate <em>hinneni</em> signals his essential posture even before he understands who is calling.</p>",
        "5": "<p>Samuel ran to Eli: &ldquo;Here I am, for you called me.&rdquo; Eli&rsquo;s denial: &ldquo;I did not call you; lie down again (<em>shub shkav</em>).&rdquo; The threefold structure of call-and-return (vv. 5, 6, 8) is a standard narrative device emphasizing the persistence and clarity of a divine call over against human confusion. The triple occurrence rules out coincidence or misperception. The three-stage initiation into prophetic calling mirrors the call-narrative patterns of the major prophets, where the prophet&rsquo;s initial resistance or confusion is overcome by divine persistence.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The second call: YHWH called again, and again Samuel ran to Eli saying &ldquo;Here I am, for you called me.&rdquo; Eli&rsquo;s denial: &ldquo;I did not call, my son (<em>beni</em>); lie down again.&rdquo; Eli&rsquo;s use of <em>beni</em> (my son) is tender &mdash; he regards Samuel as a ward. The narrative irony is sharp: the child who is not his son is more truly a son than those who are. Ps 2:7 (&ldquo;You are my Son; today I have begotten you&rdquo;) and Heb 1:5 use the father-son language for the divine call of the ultimate Son; the Samuel narrative is a type of divine adoption-through-call.</p>",
        "7": "<p>&ldquo;Now Samuel did not yet know the LORD (<em>lo yada&rsquo; et-YHWH</em>), and the word of the LORD had not yet been revealed to him (<em>terem yiggaleh elav</em>).&rdquo; Samuel&rsquo;s failure to recognize the divine call is not spiritual dullness but inexperience. He has grown up in the sanctuary, serving YHWH faithfully, but has not yet had a personal divine encounter. The prophetic word comes to the human ear before it is recognized as such &mdash; a distinction between information and encounter that marks genuine prophetic initiation.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The third call and the third trip to Eli; then &ldquo;Eli understood that the LORD was calling the boy (<em>vayavin Eli ki YHWH qore&rsquo; la-na&rsquo;ar</em>).&rdquo; Eli&rsquo;s recognition is the turning point. The aged priest who has failed spiritually in so many ways performs here an act of genuine service: he recognizes divine activity and channels it toward the child. There is pathos in the spiritual director whose own house is condemned serving as the guide for the one who will replace him. Eli&rsquo;s role at this moment is analogous to John the Baptist&rsquo;s: pointing beyond himself to the one who comes after (John 1:27).</p>",
        "9": "<p>Eli&rsquo;s instruction: &ldquo;If he calls you, you shall say, &lsquo;Speak, LORD, for your servant (<em>ki shome&rsquo;a avdekha</em>) is listening.&rsquo;&rdquo; The formula of the receptive servant reverses the common human posture of speaking and expecting to be heard. Isaiah&rsquo;s &ldquo;Here I am; send me&rdquo; (Isa 6:8) shares the structure of readiness for divine communication. Mary&rsquo;s &ldquo;I am the Lord&rsquo;s servant; let it be to me according to your word&rdquo; (Luke 1:38) is the New Covenant version of Samuel&rsquo;s posture &mdash; the receptive servant opened to transformative divine address.</p>",
        "10": "<p>YHWH came and stood (<em>vayavo YHWH vayityatzev</em>), calling as before: &ldquo;Samuel! Samuel!&rdquo; &mdash; the double name-call that marks moments of special divine address throughout the OT (Abraham: Gen 22:11; Jacob: Gen 46:2; Moses: Exod 3:4). The doubled name signals urgency and the gravity of what follows. Samuel answered with the receptive formula Eli taught him; YHWH proceeds to reveal his word.</p>",
        "11": "<p>&ldquo;Behold, I am about to do something in Israel that will make the ears of everyone who hears it tingle (<em>tetzallenah shetei oznahv</em>).&rdquo; The tingling ears formula signals an oracle of overwhelming significance. It appears again in 2 Kgs 21:12 and Jer 19:3, both pronouncements of catastrophic divine action. YHWH&rsquo;s first direct word to Samuel is not an encouraging commission but a judgment oracle against Eli&rsquo;s house. The prophetic vocation begins not with comfort but with truth about divine judgment.</p>",
        "12": "<p>&ldquo;On that day I will carry out against Eli everything I have spoken concerning his house, from beginning to end (<em>heichel ve&rsquo;killah</em>).&rdquo; The finality of the oracle &mdash; from beginning to end, nothing omitted &mdash; emphasizes totality. The contrast with divine mercy (which endures forever, Ps 136) is striking: judgment is also total when it comes, but it comes only after sustained patience and warning.</p>",
        "13": "<p>&ldquo;His sons were blaspheming God (<em>meqallelim lahem</em>) and he did not rebuke them (<em>lo kihah bahem</em>).&rdquo; The verb <em>qalal</em> (curse/treat with contempt) is used here for what Eli&rsquo;s sons did to God. The indictment of Eli is precisely: he knew (<em>yada&rsquo;</em>) and did not restrain (<em>kihah</em>). Knowledge plus inaction equals complicity. James 3:1 (teachers judged more strictly) and Heb 13:17 (leaders give an account for those in their care) apply the same standard to NT leadership.</p>",
        "14": "<p>&ldquo;The iniquity of Eli&rsquo;s house shall never be atoned for by sacrifice or offering (<em>im-yithkhapper avon beit eli bizevach uminchah ad olam</em>).&rdquo; One of the most sobering statements in the OT: a sin beyond sacrifice-and-offering atonement. The Levitical system provided for most sins, but Eli&rsquo;s house has crossed into the territory of the <em>yad ramah</em> (high-handed sin) of Num 15:30-31 &mdash; deliberate defiance for which no atonement is prescribed. Heb 10:26-27 uses similar logic for willful apostasy after receiving the knowledge of the truth.</p>",
        "15": "<p>Samuel lay until morning, then opened the doors of the house of YHWH. He was afraid to tell Eli the vision (<em>the mar&rsquo;eh</em>). The narrative notes that Samuel opens the sanctuary doors &mdash; his practical morning duty that frames the extraordinary event of the night. The ordinary and the extraordinary are woven together: even after receiving a devastating prophetic revelation, life continues in its quotidian rhythms. Prophets are not exempted from ordinary obligations by revelatory experience.</p>",
        "16": "<p>Eli called Samuel: &ldquo;Samuel, my son (<em>beni</em>).&rdquo; Samuel replied &ldquo;Here I am (<em>hinneni</em>)&rdquo; &mdash; the same word he used in response to the divine call. The word now carries double resonance: he is present and ready both for God and for Eli. Eli&rsquo;s request that follows &mdash; &ldquo;Do not hide it from me&rdquo; &mdash; shows more courage than his past behavior; he chooses to hear the truth rather than avoid it. Job&rsquo;s demand to hear from God even when the answer was devastating (Job 13:3, 22) shares this posture of demanding difficult truth.</p>",
        "17": "<p>Eli&rsquo;s charge: &ldquo;What did he say to you? Do not hide it from me. May God deal with you severely if you hide anything from me.&rdquo; The standard Hebrew oath formula invokes divine punishment for concealment. Eli uses the language of divine sovereignty he has failed to apply to his sons &mdash; he invokes YHWH&rsquo;s judgment on potential concealment even while having tolerated his sons&rsquo; blasphemy. But the request is also courageous: Eli is demanding the full truth about his own condemnation.</p>",
        "18": "<p>Samuel told everything and hid nothing. Eli&rsquo;s response: &ldquo;He is the LORD (<em>YHWH hu</em>). Let him do what seems right in his eyes (<em>ha-tov be-einav ya&rsquo;aseh</em>).&rdquo; Whatever Eli&rsquo;s spiritual state, the words are theologically correct: YHWH&rsquo;s assessment of what is right governs outcomes, not human preference. The acceptance of divine judgment &mdash; even against oneself &mdash; is a spiritual posture Job models (Job 1:21: &ldquo;the LORD gave and the LORD has taken away; blessed be the name of the LORD&rdquo;).</p>",
        "20": "<p>&ldquo;All Israel from Dan to Beersheba knew that Samuel had been established as a prophet of the LORD (<em>ne&rsquo;eman Samuel le-navi laYHWH</em>).&rdquo; The formula &ldquo;from Dan to Beersheba&rdquo; is the standard north-to-south expression for the entire land (Judg 20:1; 2 Sam 3:10). The verb <em>ne&rsquo;eman</em> (confirmed/established) is related to <em>amen</em> &mdash; his prophetic status is ratified by fulfilled prophecy. Deut 18:22&rsquo;s criterion for a true prophet (his words come true) is the implicit standard being applied here.</p>",
        "21": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD continued to appear (<em>vayyoseph YHWH lehera&rsquo;ot</em>) at Shiloh, for the LORD revealed himself to Samuel at Shiloh through the word of the LORD.&rdquo; The repeated divine appearance through the medium of Samuel marks the beginning of a new era of revelation. The phrase &ldquo;through the word of the LORD (<em>bidfar YHWH</em>)&rdquo; identifies the prophetic word as the primary vehicle of divine self-disclosure. John 1:1-3 elevates this to its maximum expression: the Word (<em>Logos</em>) is not merely a vehicle of revelation but divine revelation in person. Samuel is the vessel through whom the word comes; Jesus <em>is</em> the Word.</p>",
    },
}


def main():
    existing = load_comm("mkt-context", "1samuel")
    merged = merge_comm(existing, SAMUEL1)
    save_comm("mkt-context", "1samuel", merged)


